# 🧭 Task-Aware Curated Context — POC Implementation Plan

> A best-practice guide for serving standardised, curated context to developers based on the task they're performing — surfaced where they work, via Port and MCP.
> Treat this as a scaffold, not a script — adapt the order to your environment and governance norms.

---

## ⚠️ Before You Start: Scope This Story

"Serve up all relevant context" is open-ended and can't be built or scored as-is. Pin these down first — the POC depends on it:

- **Which task?** Scope the POC to *one* concrete task. Your example — **developing a new API** — is the right one.
- **What context, exactly?** For "new API," that likely means: existing similar APIs, the API standard/blueprint, the golden-path template, owning team & reviewers, related services & dependencies, security/compliance requirements, and the "what good looks like" scorecard.
- **Surfaced where?** In the Port UI, or pushed into the IDE via MCP? (The IDE/MCP route is the differentiator.)
- **What's the outcome?** Add the missing "so that" — e.g. "so that I start a new API with the right standards and context in minutes instead of hunting across wikis, repos, and people."

---

## 🎯 The Goal

When a developer starts a defined task, Port assembles the **curated, standardised context** relevant to *that* task and serves it where they work — so they don't hunt across wikis, repos, dashboards, and people to find what they need to do it right.

**POC scope:** one task — *developing a new API* — with a curated context set served into the IDE via MCP.

### 📊 Before → After

| Before | After |
|---|---|
| Starting a new API means piecing context together from multiple wikis, repos, and Slack threads — slow, inconsistent, and easy to miss a standard. ~[X] min/hours per task, variable quality. | Port serves the curated, standardised context for the task in one place (and in the IDE), so the developer starts right the first time. |

> 💡 *Context/"cognitive load" stories are hard to quantify. Anchor ROI to a concrete metric for the chosen task — e.g. time-to-first-commit on a new API, or onboarding ramp time. Pairing this with a golden-path action (below) makes the saving measurable.*

---

## 🧱 1. Model the Context (Data Model)

**Goal:** the things that make up "context for a new API" exist as catalog entities the platform can assemble.

- 🗂️ **Blueprints** — model the context sources: **API** (existing ones to learn from), **API Standard / Guideline**, **Golden Path Template**, **Service**, **Team / Owner**, and **Doc / Runbook** references. → [Blueprints](https://docs.port.io/build-your-software-catalog/define-your-data-model/setup-blueprint/)
- 🔗 **Relations** — connect API → Standard, API → owning Team, Service → related APIs, Template → Standard. These relations are how "relevant context" is computed rather than hand-curated. → [Relate blueprints](https://docs.port.io/build-your-software-catalog/define-your-data-model/relate-blueprints/)
- 🔌 **Core integrations (1–2 max)** — the SCM ([GitHub](https://docs.port.io/build-your-software-catalog/sync-data-to-catalog/git/github/) / [GitLab](https://docs.port.io/build-your-software-catalog/sync-data-to-catalog/git/gitlab/)) for existing APIs/services. Favor Port-hosted setup; **mock standards/templates/docs via UPSERT** for the POC.
- 🌱 **Seed entities** — populate a realistic set of APIs, one or two standards, and a golden-path template so the curated context is rich enough to demo.

✅ **Done when:** the entities that constitute "new-API context" exist and relate.

---

## 👀 2. The Curated Context Experience

**Goal:** for the chosen task, the right context is assembled in one curated place — not scattered.

- 📄 **Task context page** — a curated view for "developing a new API" that pulls together standards, the golden-path template, similar existing APIs, owners/reviewers, and the readiness scorecard. → [Catalog pages](https://docs.port.io/customize-pages-dashboards-and-plugins/page/catalog-page/)
- 🎚️ **"What good looks like" scorecard** — show the API standards as a scorecard so the developer sees the bar up front. → [Scorecards](https://docs.port.io/promote-scorecards/)
- 🧩 **Curation logic** — use relations + filters so the context is *computed* for the task, keeping it current automatically rather than a static page someone maintains. → [Dashboards](https://docs.port.io/customize-pages-dashboards-and-plugins/dashboards/)

✅ **Done when:** a developer starting a new API sees one curated, current context set instead of hunting.

---

## 🧞 3. Serve It Into the IDE (MCP) — the Differentiator

**Goal:** the context meets the developer where they work, not in a separate tab.

- 💻 **Port MCP in the IDE** — expose the curated context via [Port MCP](https://docs.port.io/ai-agents/port-mcp-server/) so the developer can ask, from VS Code / Cursor, "what do I need to know to build a new payments API?" and get the standards, template, similar APIs, and owners — without leaving the editor. → [AI agents](https://docs.port.io/ai-agents/overview/)
- 🤖 **Context agent** — the agent assembles task-relevant context on demand by traversing the catalog, rather than the developer navigating to it.

✅ **Done when:** the developer pulls curated, task-relevant context into the IDE in one natural-language ask.

---

## ⭐ What Turns This Into a Winning POC Story

Serving context is **read-only** — and a context page alone is something Backstage or Cortex can approximate. The differentiation (and the measurable ROI) comes from making it *actionable*:

> ### 💬 Suggested Agentic + Action Story
> *As a developer, I want to ask Port for the context to build a new API and have the agent not only surface the standards, template, and similar APIs — but offer to scaffold the new API from the golden-path template, pre-filled with the right owner, standards, and registration — so that I go from "I need to build an API" to a compliant, catalogued starting point in one step, in the IDE.*
>
> **Why it matters:** this turns a read-only context lookup into an agent that **acts** (MCP context → golden-path scaffold → auto-registration), combining catalog context, autonomous workflow, and a self-service action. That's what makes it unmistakably Port — and gives you a real before/after to measure.

